::: {.doc-subject}

Forest plot of hazard ratios (or other contrasts) with confidence intervals.
:::

::: {.doc-usage-source}
Usage

[Source](https://github.com/rich-iannone/greenwood/blob/main/greenwood/viz/_forest.py#L145-L301){target="_blank" rel="noopener"}
:::

::: {.doc-signature .doc-Kind.FUNCTION}
```python
viz.plot_forest(
    result,
    *,
    scale=None,
    exponentiate=True,
    title=None,
    term_labels=None,
    xlab=None,
    backend="altair",
    width=600,
    height=400
)
```
:::

::: {.doc-text}

Accepts a fitted `~greenwood.CoxPH` object or any tidy DataFrame that contains
`term`, `estimate`, `ci_lower` (or `conf_low`), and `ci_upper` (or
`conf_high`) columns. The latter supports subgroup forest plots where you already
have the summary estimates (e.g., from running Cox per subgroup and calling
`~greenwood.tidy` on each).
:::

## Parameters {.doc-parameters}

::: {.doc-definition-items}
<code>[result]{.doc-parameter-name}[:]{.doc-parameter-annotation-sep} [Any]{.doc-parameter-annotation}</code>

:   A fitted `CoxPH` result object, or a tidy DataFrame with one row per term.

<code>[scale]{.doc-parameter-name}[:]{.doc-parameter-annotation-sep} [Literal[[&quot;log&quot;]{.st}, [&quot;linear&quot;]{.st}] | None]{.doc-parameter-annotation} [=]{.doc-parameter-default-sep .op} [None]{.doc-parameter-default}</code>

:   X-axis scale: `"log"` for hazard ratios (reference line at HR = 1) or
    `"linear"` for differences (reference line at 0). When `None` (default),
    the scale is inferred: `"log"` for a CoxPH object with `exponentiate=True`,
    `"linear"` otherwise. Pass `scale="log"` explicitly when supplying a
    DataFrame of hazard ratios.

<code>[exponentiate]{.doc-parameter-name}[:]{.doc-parameter-annotation-sep} [bool]{.doc-parameter-annotation} [=]{.doc-parameter-default-sep .op} [[True]{.va}]{.doc-parameter-default}</code>

:   When *result* is a `CoxPH` object: if `True` (default) extract hazard ratios;
    if `False` extract log-hazard coefficients. Ignored when *result* is a
    DataFrame or when *scale* is set explicitly.

<code>[title]{.doc-parameter-name}[:]{.doc-parameter-annotation-sep} [str | None]{.doc-parameter-annotation} [=]{.doc-parameter-default-sep .op} [None]{.doc-parameter-default}</code>

:   Plot title. Defaults to `None` (no title).

<code>[term_labels]{.doc-parameter-name}[:]{.doc-parameter-annotation-sep} [dict[str, str] | None]{.doc-parameter-annotation} [=]{.doc-parameter-default-sep .op} [None]{.doc-parameter-default}</code>

:   Optional mapping from internal term names to display labels, e.g.
    `{"age": "Age (years)", "sex": "Female vs. Male"}`. Only the terms listed are
    renamed. Others keep their original names.

<code>[xlab]{.doc-parameter-name}[:]{.doc-parameter-annotation-sep} [str | None]{.doc-parameter-annotation} [=]{.doc-parameter-default-sep .op} [None]{.doc-parameter-default}</code>

:   X-axis label. Defaults to `"Hazard Ratio"` for log scale and `"Estimate"`
    for linear scale.

<code>[backend]{.doc-parameter-name}[:]{.doc-parameter-annotation-sep} [Literal[[&quot;altair&quot;]{.st}, [&quot;plotnine&quot;]{.st}]]{.doc-parameter-annotation} [=]{.doc-parameter-default-sep .op} [[&quot;altair&quot;]{.st}]{.doc-parameter-default}</code>

:   Plotting backend: `"altair"` (default, interactive) or `"plotnine"`
    (composable ggplot2-style object).

<code>[width]{.doc-parameter-name}[:]{.doc-parameter-annotation-sep} [int]{.doc-parameter-annotation} [=]{.doc-parameter-default-sep .op} [[600]{.dv}]{.doc-parameter-default}</code>

:   Plot width in pixels (default 600). Altair only.

<code>[height]{.doc-parameter-name}[:]{.doc-parameter-annotation-sep} [int]{.doc-parameter-annotation} [=]{.doc-parameter-default-sep .op} [[400]{.dv}]{.doc-parameter-default}</code>

:   Plot height in pixels (default 400). Altair only.
:::

## Returns {.doc-returns}

::: {.doc-definition-items}
<code> [altair.Chart or plotnine.ggplot]{.doc-parameter-annotation}</code>

:   A composable chart object. Add layers, scales, or themes using the `+` operator
    (plotnine) or `.properties()` / `.interactive()` (Altair).
:::

## Examples {.doc-examples}

Fit a Cox model and draw a forest plot of hazard ratios:

::: {#772d2abb .cell execution_count=1}
``` {.python .cell-code}
import greenwood as gw

# Load data and fit a Cox model with three covariates
lung = gw.load_dataset("lung", backend="polars")
y = gw.Surv.right(lung["time"], event=(lung["status"] == 2))
cox = gw.CoxPH().fit(y, lung[["age", "sex", "ph.ecog"]])

# Draw a forest plot of hazard ratios with confidence intervals
gw.plot_forest(cox)
```

